>Introduction

This research project is to carry out some simple analysis on time series data extracted from Insight(Cases from 2011 to 2015) and forecast revenue of the next 10 month from now on.

1. Read data from Insigtht and Pre-processing

2. Make it as time series data

revtimeseries <- ts(alldata.ready$sumofRev, frequency=12, start=c(2011,12))

3. Plot Time Series

Revenue Plot for each month(2012-2015)

This plot shows that it appears an additive mode is not appropriate for describing this time series, since the size of the seasonal fluctuations and random fluctuations seem to increase with the level of the time series. Thus, we may need to transform the time series by calculating the natural log of the original data in order to get a transformed time series that can be described using an additive model.

It appears that the size of the seasonal fluctuations and random fluctuations in the log-transformed time series seem to be roughly constant over time, and do not depend on the level of the time series. Thus, this log-transformed time series can probably be described using an additive model.

Here we would estimate the trend through smoothing time series data to help look at the trend of data. Thus, we use a simple moving average(SMA) method to smooth time series data with order=9.

The data smoothed with a simple moving average of order 9 gives a clearer picture of the trend component, and we can see that the revenue seems to have continuously increase from 2012 to 2015, and specially fast increase from 2013 to 2014.

Next we will estimate the seasonal component, trend component and random component through decomposing time series data to have a look at the seasonal, trend and random object respectively.

4. Revenue Forecast Using Holt-Winters Exponential Smoothing

Considering this time seires using additive model with increasing trend and seasonality, we use the Holt-Winters exponetial smoothing to make forcast. Typically, 1.simple exponential smoothing is using for an additive model with constant level and no seasonality; 2.Holt’s Exponential smoothing is using for an additive model with increasing or decreasing trend and no seasonality; 3.Holt-Winters Exponetial smoothing is using for an additive model with increasing or decreasing trend and seasonality.

4.1 Fit the model
## Holt-Winters exponential smoothing with trend and additive seasonal component.
## 
## Call:
## HoltWinters(x = logrevtimeseries)
## 
## Smoothing parameters:
##  alpha: 0.7714782
##  beta : 0
##  gamma: 0.3593684

## s6  -0.4866282
## s7  -0.6414855
## s8  -0.2882814
## s9   0.7778771
## s10  0.6084971
## s11  0.7668806
## s12  0.1993514

## [1] 95.57493

Here alpha, beta, and gamma denote the level, slope and seasonal component respectively. The value of alpha(0.77) is relatively high, indicating that the estimate of the level at the current time point is mainly based on current observation. And beta(0), indicating that estimate of the slope is not updated over the time series and equal to its initial value, that is the slope of the trend remains roughly the same. In contrast, the value of gamma (0.35) is low, indicating that the estimate of the seasonal component at the current time point is based upon recent observations and most distant observations.The plot is indicating it is very successful in predicting the seasonal trough, which occur roughly in July

4.3 Accuracy Estimation

Below detect if there are correlations between forecast errors for successive predictions.We can investigate whether the predictive model can be improved upon by checking whether the in-sample forecast errors show non-zero autocorrelations at lags 1-20, by making a correlogram and carrying out the Ljung-Box test. The correlogram shows that the autocorrelations for the in-sample forecast errors do not exceed the significance bounds for lags 1-20. Furthermore, the p-value for Ljung-Box test is 0.9, indicating that there is little evidence of non-zero autocorrelations at lags 1-20. 

## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  Revseriesforecasts2$residuals
## X-squared = 5.696, df = 20, p-value = 0.9993

4.4 Conclusion for forecast with HoltWinters exponential smoothing model:

Through above plots, we can discover that the distribution of forecast errors is roughly centred on zero, and is more or less normally distributed with mean zero. And The Ljung-Box test showed that there is little evidence of non-zero autocorrelations in the forecast errors. This suggests that the Holt-Winters exponential smoothing used here provides an adequate predictive model for revenue forecast, which probably cannot be improved upon. Furthermore, the assumptions that the 80% and 95% predictions intervals were based upon (that there are no autocorrelations in the forecast errors, and the forecast errors are normally distributed with mean zero and constant variance) are probably valid.

5. ARIMA Model used to make Forecast

ARIMA models are defined for stationary time series. Therefore, if you start off with a non-stationary time series, you will first need to ‘difference’ the time series until you obtain a stationary time series. If you have to difference the time series d times to obtain a stationary series, then you have an ARIMA(p,d,q) model, where d is the order of differencing used.

5.1.Difference

* USing diff(),maybe over and over to be stationary mean, in order to get the stationary time series

This plot appears that it is stationary time series ARIMA can be applicable for.

5.2.Select ARIMA Model

We need to find appropriate values of p and q for ARIMA(p,d,q) model. To do this, usually need to examine the correlogram and partial correlogram of the stationary time series through “acf()” and “pacf()” respectively.

* Get the values of autocorrelations

## 
## Autocorrelations of series 'revtimeseriesdiff', by lag
## 
## 0.0000 0.0833 0.1667 0.2500 0.3333 0.4167 0.5000 0.5833 0.6667 0.7500 
##  1.000  0.157 -0.070 -0.115  0.029 -0.081  0.012 -0.180 -0.018  0.118 
## 0.8333 0.9167 1.0000 1.0833 1.1667 1.2500 1.3333 1.4167 1.5000 1.5833 
## -0.064  0.123  0.025 -0.098 -0.103  0.093 -0.059  0.057  0.036 -0.020 
## 1.6667 
##  0.062

We can see that no lags exceeds the significance bound. and lags tail off to zero.=> q=0

* Get the values of partial autocorrelations

## 
## Partial autocorrelations of series 'revtimeseriesdiff', by lag
##

##  0.250 -0.113 -0.091 -0.003  0.018 -0.009  0.011  0.082 -0.051  0.041

We can see that no lags exceeds the significance bound. and lags tail off to zero.=>p=0 ,so we can get ARIMA(0,1,0) model.

* We can also use the auto.arima() to automatically get the values of p,d and q.

5.5.Conclusion

The histogram of the time series shows that the forecast errors are roughly normally distributed and the mean seems to be close to zero. Therefore, it is plausible that the forecast errors are normally distributed with mean zero and constant variance.Since successive forecast errors do not seem to be correlated, and the forecast errors seem to be normally distributed with mean zero and constant variance, the ARIMA(1,0,0) does seem to provide an adequate predictive model for the Revenue time seires data.

Considering IPG revenue time series data has some correlations between successive points of times series(with the ecosystem built up with partners, more patients, physicians, facility and Manufacturers enrolled in this system, revenue will increase with the time going on), ARIMA is more better model to predict the revenue of time series data.
